<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-261-832  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 261 832.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Federal Computer Week  March 12 1990 v4 n10 p14(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>CALS delays won't stall standards. (Department of Defensecontinues work on the Computer-Aided Acquisition and LogisticsSupport-related standards)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Smithmidford, Robert.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The US Department of Defense (DOD) and industry continuedevelopment of Computer-Aided Acquisition and Logistics Support(CALS)-related standards despite a hold on CALS programs becauseof budget cuts and force reductions.andP;  CALS programs are developingautomated methods for streamlining weapons design, management,purchase and maintenance.andP;  Examples include an Army project usinga laptop PC to provide online maintenance information for theAbrams tank and a $520 million project to develop an Air ForceTechnical Order Management System.andP;  The CALS Steering Group iscontinuing the development of a CALS standards framework.andP;  Anexample standard being developed is a revised Standard GeneralizedMarkup Language (SGML) for identifying elements in a document.andP;  UScommittees are attempting to reach consensus on SGML and otherstandards before submitting them to the International StandardsOrganization.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     StandardsResearch and DevelopmentWeaponsAutomationProduct DevelopmentMaintenancePerformance ImprovementUnited States. Department of Defense.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>